romoted from my direct manager's position (head of research) and members of management are generally very accessible. They are reasonable in responding to your requests as well. They will always hear out your argument, and either help you implement your recommendations, or give you a very logically reasoned out answer as to why they will not pursue it. It leaves a good feeling even when you disagree.-The firm is a good combination of being innovative and being practical. They give you a lot of room to pursue the research problem however you want, and generally give you the support to do so. Though, of course, they also apply a reasonable amount of pressure so you can come out with research conclusions to help the business move forward.Cons-Coming with the inflection in growth and the career growth opportunities is a less defined culture in a fast growing firm. Hiring is happening very quickly to match the success of the firm business wise, and the outlook is great. However, it is uncertain how the culture can shift. Management is investing a lot to preserve the small company feel, but only time will tell how the cultural transition will work out.-Boston cost of living is on the rise. I still like the city, but don't expect too much of a drop in cost of living when moving here from New York.Advice to ManagementContinue working hard to define the culture as the place grows, and you will end up with a prosperous and successful firm.Share on FacebookShare on TwitterShare on WhatsAppShare via EmailCopy LinkLink Copied!Flag as InappropriateFlag as InappropriateHelpful (1) Numeric Investors LLC Response seconds agoEdit • Delete Numeric Investors LLC 2017-03-08 11:05 PST Jan 24, 2017"Place where you can architect your career goals yourself"StarStarStarStarStarWork/Life BalanceCulture & ValuesCareer OpportunitiesComp & BenefitsSenior ManagementCurrent Employee - Anonymous Employee in Boston, MACurrent Employee - Anonymous Employee in Boston, MARecommendsPositive OutlookAppro